                      <td valign="top" height="100%"><font face="arial" size="2" color="#000000"><span class="spnMessageText" id="msg"> knochi: You do realize you fell exaclty into the trap I mentioned? As I said - developers can say anything and everything about what was intended.  The bottomline is that WE *don't* know what's intended.  *THEY* do, but they can change it or twist it as they please because we are never told exactly what it's supposed to be used for.  That said:<br /><br /><blockquote id="quote"><font size="2" face="arial" id="quote">quote:<hr height="1" noshade id="quote">Spell duration foci designed to affect DoTs (the Affliction line) should now work reliably.<hr height="1" noshade id="quote"></blockquote id="quote"></font id="quote"><br /><br />This is a good proof on your part.  I must've missed it way back.  However, this only says what the foci was designed to affect, but did not exclude anything.  The devs did not come out and say, at this point or any other point, that root/mez/charm/etc. were NOT supposed to be affected by the affliction line of focus effects (which, by the way, were not only called "affliction" - many effects had similar bearings but were named things like Accursed Extension (SoLR), Focus of Mediocrity, Vengeance of Time (that really says alot about what that's supposed to do)) - until they did the actual nerf.<br /><br />Of course, by that time, it was way too late.  Moreover, they had fallen into the exact habit I mentioned them having: calling something as being "unintended" at the time of the nerf as the justification for the nerf.  Now in truth, I don't really care if it was intended or not, because that doesn't matter, which is exactly my point.  Heck, there is a whole set of very viable arguments that claim the devs did the nerf NOT because the affliction line was not working as intended, but because they wanted to nerf CHARM indirectly.<br /><br />Personally, I see this as two failures on the developer's part: 1) failure to communicate, which caused many people to spend DKPs and plat on items that were never "intended" to work the way they thought and 2) failure to correct a potentially devastating bug with the affliction series of focus effects until, according to your dates, EIGHT months later.  That's simply unacceptable for a supposedly professional company, and is wholly contrary to the idea of intention.  If you're going to leave a bug in the game for that long, you better either state it outright as something you're going to fix or be prepared for it to become a part of the feature list.<br /><br /><blockquote id="quote"><font size="2" face="arial" id="quote">quote:<hr height="1" noshade id="quote"> Edantik, everyone knew that AE was intended for dot's only because look at the word. AFFLICTION.<hr height="1" noshade id="quote"></blockquote id="quote"></font id="quote"><br /><br />And slow is not an affliction? And root is not an affliction? Definition of affliction from dictionary.com:<br /><br />af·flic·tion    ( P )  Pronunciation Key  (-flkshn)<br />n. <br />A condition of pain, suffering, or distress. See Synonyms at trial. <br />A cause of pain, suffering, or distress. See Synonyms at burden1. <br /><br />Notice the conditions: pain, suffering, AND distress.  Is slow not a form of distress? Is root not a form of distress? Is charm not a form of suffering or distress?<br /><br />But I really shouldn't even need to point this out.  EQ has a habit of using words for their vagueness.  Just look at Bedlam: where in the definition of the word do you see regeant-free rune?<br /><br /><blockquote id="quote"><font size="2" face="arial" id="quote">quote:<hr height="1" noshade id="quote">That being said: I valued your posts in the past, because one noticed that you used your brain before you posted them. Hope you find your way back, because we got enough from the bitter whiners faction here already.<hr height="1" noshade id="quote"></blockquote id="quote"></font id="quote"><br /><br />I always use my brain before I post something and this is no exception.  Perhaps it does not fit into your idea of a great post because it is, after all, contrary to popular opinion, but that does not mean I did not think before I posted it.<br /></span id="msg"></font><br><br></td>
